  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT243-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">vaṉpoṟaiyetiraḻintu colliyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered in desolation in the face of encouragement. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT243">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>māṉaṭi yaṉṉa kavaṭṭilai yaṭumpiṉ</l>
          <l>ṟārmaṇi yaṉṉa voṇpūk koḻuti</l>
          <l>yoṇṭoṭi makaḷir vaṇṭa layarum</l>
          <l>puḷḷimiḻ peruṅkaṭaṟ cērppaṉai</l>
          <l>yuḷḷēṉ ṟōḻi paṭīiyareṉ kaṇṇē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>I won't remember, friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent">the man from the coast of the great sea buzzing with birds,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">where women with bright bracelets are engaged in play</l>
          <l rend="indent2">after having picked flowers bright as sapphires for a garland <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">tārmaṇi</term>: these might either refer to blue flowers for a
            garland, or, as T.V.G. takes it, flowers resembling "bells on a string" (cf. KT 182).</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent3">of the Aṭumpu plants [forked] like a stag's foot.</l>
          <l rend="indent7">May my eyes close.</l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="5b">
            <l>I don’t remember ... , while my eyes suffer. <note place="foot">
                <term xml:lang="ta">paṭīiyar</term> can also be read as an infinitive and thus as a
              clause, not an independent sentence. Possibly the many nuances of the root <term xml:lang="ta">paṭu-tal</term> are exploited here to have a kind of double
              entendre: SHE has decided not to remember HIM any more, but it is uncertain whether
              her eyes will not betray her.</note>
            </l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
